  "prompt": "How is WhatsApp able to show the blurred image even after deleting the original copy from the gallery?",
  "response": "WhatsApp stores a copy of received media files (images, videos, etc.) in its own internal storage directory, separate from the device's gallery. Here's a detailed explanation:\n\n1. When you receive an image on WhatsApp:\n- The image is automatically saved in WhatsApp's internal storage folder\n- A thumbnail/preview is also cached for quick loading\n- Even if you delete the image from your gallery, WhatsApp's copy remains intact\n\n2. Specific storage location:\n- Android: /storage/emulated/0/Android/media/com.whatsapp/WhatsApp/Media/\n- iOS: Within the WhatsApp app's internal storage\n\n3. Thumbnail/preview mechanism:\n- WhatsApp creates a compressed, blurred version of the image\n- This preview is stored separately and can be quickly loaded\n- Requires minimal storage space\n\n4. Additional storage details:\n- Media files have different quality versions (original, compressed)\n- Different folders for images, videos, documents\n- Controlled by WhatsApp's internal file management system\n\n5. Privacy note:\n- Users can disable auto-download of media\n- Can clear WhatsApp media cache manually in app settings\n\nThis approach ensures quick access to media and provides a smooth user experience, even after original file deletion.",
